 1. Overall Completion Rate
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  In this dataset, 62.1% of trips were successfully completed.
  That means roughly 37.9% of bookings didn't work out. The
  two biggest reasons were 'No Driver Found' (7.0%) and
  'Driver Cancelled' (18.0%). Together, these two account for
  most of the failed rides — which suggests the problem is
  more on the supply side than the customer side.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  2. Rush Hour Has More Cancellations
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  During morning and evening rush hours (7–9 AM and 5–8 PM),
  the cancellation rate goes up to 38.0%, compared to 37.8%
  during quieter hours. That's a 0.1% difference. This makes
  sense — when everyone is trying to book at the same time,
  there simply aren't enough drivers to go around.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  3. Some Areas Are Harder to Get a Ride
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  'Kashmere Gate ISBT' has one of the highest cancellation
  rates at 47.1%. Areas like Noida Sector and Gurgaon Sector
  also show up repeatedly as high-risk zones. This could be
  because drivers avoid these routes, or because traffic makes
  it harder to complete the trip — either way, users in these
  areas consistently have a worse experience.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  4. Not Everyone Gets Equal Service
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Looking at the data, areas that are further from the city
  centre or seem to be lower-income tend to have higher
  cancellation rates and longer wait times. This is something
  I found worth highlighting — if a platform only focuses on
  profitable routes, it might unintentionally make it harder
  for some people to get around. This isn't just a business
  problem, it's a fairness issue too.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  5. What the Model Suggests We Can Do
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Based on the Random Forest model from Notebook 03, the two
  strongest predictors of cancellation are ride distance and
  time of day. From this, a few practical ideas come to mind:
  (a) for long-distance rides during peak hours, the app could
  pre-assign a backup driver; (b) drivers could be offered
  small incentives to take rides in high-cancellation areas;
  (c) if the model detects a high cancellation risk early, the
  app could adjust pricing to keep both drivers and passengers
  committed to the trip.
